# Dup-detection benchmark — Gate B.3 latency surface

## Why this notebook exists

Gate B.3 (per spec §5 Stream B) requires a query-performance benchmark on the
embedding index: file 1000 fixture cards, run `Manillum.Archive.find_duplicates/3`
against the resulting archive, and confirm latency is acceptable for the
cataloging pipeline's per-draft dup-check call. This notebook is that surface.

The query exercised here is the same one `Capture.Changes.RunCataloging` runs
once per draft. With 1000 filed cards and an HNSW index on `cards.embedding`
using `vector_cosine_ops`, a single `find_duplicates` call should be in the
single-millisecond range on a warm cache.

## Connecting

Run Livebook on the host. Start the app with
`iex --name manillum@127.0.0.1 --cookie <cookie> -S mix phx.server`, then point
Livebook's **Runtime → Mix standalone** at this repo.

> **Cost note.** This benchmark embeds 1000 fixture cards via the OpenAI
> `text-embedding-3-small` API. At $0.02 / 1M tokens and ~30 tokens per fixture,
> a full run is ~$0.0006 — well under a cent. The fixtures are reused across
> runs (same seed) so a cold dev DB pays once.

## Setup — fresh user + module aliases

```elixir
alias Manillum.Archive
alias Manillum.Archive.Card
alias Manillum.AI.Embedding.OpenAI, as: Embedder

email = "bench-#{System.system_time(:millisecond)}@example.com"
user = Ash.Seed.seed!(Manillum.Accounts.User, %{email: email})
user.id
```

## Generate 1000 fixture cards

We don't need realistic content — we need 1000 distinct `back` strings whose
embeddings span a reasonable corner of vector space. Random ASCII paragraphs
work: each one produces a different embedding, the HNSW index clusters them as
it would real cards, and the query path is identical to production.

```elixir
defmodule Bench do
  def random_paragraph(n_words) do
    for _ <- 1..n_words, into: "" do
      len = Enum.random(3..10)
      word = for _ <- 1..len, into: "", do: <<Enum.random(?a..?z)>>
      word <> " "
    end
  end
end

:rand.seed(:exsplus, {1, 2, 3})

drawer_pool = [:ANT, :CLA, :MED, :REN, :EAR, :MOD, :CON]

fixtures =
  for i <- 1..1000 do
    drawer = Enum.random(drawer_pool)
    year = Enum.random(-1500..2000)
    date_token = if year < 0, do: "#{abs(year)}BC", else: "#{year}AD"

    %{
      slug: "FIXTURE-#{i}",
      drawer: drawer,
      date_token: date_token,
      back: "Fixture #{i}: " <> Bench.random_paragraph(80)
    }
  end

length(fixtures)
```

## Embed in batches; persist as filed cards

OpenAI accepts up to 2048 inputs per `/v1/embeddings` call, but we batch at 100
to keep memory and HTTP payload reasonable.

```elixir
{embed_ms, embeddings} =
  :timer.tc(fn ->
    fixtures
    |> Enum.chunk_every(100)
    |> Enum.flat_map(fn chunk ->
      texts = Enum.map(chunk, & &1.back)
      {:ok, vectors} = Embedder.generate(texts, [])
      vectors
    end)
  end)

IO.puts("Embedded #{length(embeddings)} fixtures in #{embed_ms / 1000} ms")
```

```elixir
{seed_ms, _} =
  :timer.tc(fn ->
    fixtures
    |> Enum.zip(embeddings)
    |> Enum.each(fn {fixture, embedding} ->
      Ash.Seed.seed!(Card, %{
        user_id: user.id,
        drawer: fixture.drawer,
        date_token: fixture.date_token,
        slug: fixture.slug,
        card_type: :event,
        front: "F",
        back: fixture.back,
        status: :filed,
        embedding: embedding
      })
    end)
  end)

IO.puts("Seeded 1000 filed cards in #{seed_ms / 1000} ms")
```

## Warm the HNSW index, then time 100 query embeddings

`find_duplicates` runs a `<=>` cosine query that the HNSW index serves. The
first query after a cold start can pull pages from disk; we warm the cache with
a few throwaway calls and then time 100 representative queries.

```elixir
# Pick 100 random fixtures' back text and embed them as if they were drafts
# coming through the cataloging pipeline.
sample_texts =
  fixtures
  |> Enum.take_random(100)
  |> Enum.map(& &1.back)

{sample_embed_ms, sample_vectors} =
  :timer.tc(fn ->
    sample_texts
    |> Enum.chunk_every(100)
    |> Enum.flat_map(fn chunk ->
      {:ok, vs} = Embedder.generate(chunk, [])
      vs
    end)
  end)

IO.puts("Embedded 100 query vectors in #{sample_embed_ms / 1000} ms")

# Warm: 5 throwaway queries.
Enum.each(Enum.take(sample_vectors, 5), fn v ->
  Archive.find_duplicates(user.id, v, threshold: 0.5, limit: 5)
end)

# Time: per-call latency over the full 100.
latencies_us =
  Enum.map(sample_vectors, fn v ->
    {us, _ids} =
      :timer.tc(fn -> Archive.find_duplicates(user.id, v, threshold: 0.5, limit: 5) end)

    us
  end)

count = length(latencies_us)
mean_us = Enum.sum(latencies_us) / count
sorted = Enum.sort(latencies_us)
p50_us = Enum.at(sorted, div(count, 2))
p95_us = Enum.at(sorted, trunc(count * 0.95))
p99_us = Enum.at(sorted, trunc(count * 0.99))
max_us = List.last(sorted)

IO.puts("""
find_duplicates latency over #{count} queries against 1000 filed cards:
  mean : #{Float.round(mean_us / 1000, 2)} ms
  p50  : #{Float.round(p50_us / 1000, 2)} ms
  p95  : #{Float.round(p95_us / 1000, 2)} ms
  p99  : #{Float.round(p99_us / 1000, 2)} ms
  max  : #{Float.round(max_us / 1000, 2)} ms
""")
```

## Sign-off — Gate B.3 latency

The cataloging pipeline calls `find_duplicates` once per draft, typically 1–3
times per Capture. With p95 well under 50 ms, dup-detection adds negligible
overhead to the LLM round-trip that dominates pipeline cost.

- [ ] mean latency < 25 ms
- [ ] p95 latency < 50 ms
- [ ] HNSW index visible in `psql` via `\d cards`
      (`cards_embedding_hnsw_idx`)
- [ ] No HNSW build warnings in Postgres logs during the seed step

If any line is red, capture the numbers + Postgres version + pgvector version
in [[runbooks/gate-b3-dup-detection]] and pause for review.
